482
53:14.460 --> 53:22.770
It's a promise problem. And like the Bernstein-Vazirani problem, the promise involves some string s that we can view as being a hidden string,

483
53:22.770 --> 53:29.610
and also like the
Bernstein-Vazirani problem, the goal is to output
this hidden string s.

484
53:29.610 --> 53:36.180
The promise is more
complicated this time though, so let's take it apart and
understand what it's saying.

485
53:36.180 --> 53:42.810
To begin, let's just read it. It says that there exists a string s having length equal to n

486
53:42.810 --> 53:50.460
such that a particular "if"
and "only if" condition is true for all choices of n bits strings x and y.

487
53:50.460 --> 53:59.010
Specifically, it must
be the case that f of x is equal to f of y if and only if one of
two possibilities holds.

488
53:59.010 --> 54:06.630
The first possibility is that x equals y, and the second possibility is that by taking the
bitwise eXclusive OR of x

489
54:06.630 --> 54:10.710
in the hidden string s, we get Y.

490
54:10.710 --> 54:15.600
This turns out to be a
pretty strict promise in the sense that most
functions won't satisfy it.

491
54:15.600 --> 54:20.850
Only very special functions
satisfy this condition.

492
54:20.850 --> 54:30.390
Now, to get a better grasp on this promise and therefore on the problem itself, we'll consider two main cases.

493
54:30.390 --> 54:34.560
The first case is that s
is the all-zero string.

494
54:34.560 --> 54:41.520
In this case, we can simplify the "if"
and "only if" statement in the promise because the bitwise
eXclusive OR of any string x

495
54:41.520 --> 54:45.570
with the all-zero string
is simply the string x.

496
54:45.570 --> 54:53.700
So the condition simplifies
to f of x is equal to f of y if and only if x equals y.

497
54:53.700 --> 54:58.140
And that's just another way of saying that f is a one to one function.

498
54:58.140 --> 55:04.440
In other words, the string f of x must be unique
for each possible string x.

499
55:04.440 --> 55:12.780
So if f is a one to one function, then the promise is indeed satisfied, specifically for s being
the all-zero string,

500
55:12.780 --> 55:17.670
and in this case, that's
the correct output.

501
55:17.670 --> 55:26.190
The second case is that s
is not the all-zero string, and what this implies is that the function f must be two to one.

502
55:26.190 --> 55:33.900
So for every input string x, there's exactly one other string that f maps to the same
string that x maps to,

503
55:33.900 --> 55:42.180
and moreover, the other string
must be the string we get by taking the bitwise
eXclusive OR of x with s.

504
55:42.180 --> 55:48.840
Another way of saying this
is that every n bit string x has a partner, and that partner is the string that we get

505
55:48.840 --> 55:53.160
by taking the bitwise eXclusive OR with s.

506
55:53.160 --> 56:01.530
Any two partners must give
us the same output string if we plug them into f, and no other strings are allowed to give us
that same output string.

507
56:01.530 --> 56:08.130
So these are necessarily distinct strings that partners produce.

508
56:08.130 --> 56:12.660
Here's an example of a function like this described by its table of values.

509
56:12.660 --> 56:16.920
So this is a function
from 3 bits to 5 bits.

510
56:16.920 --> 56:25.902
If we stare at this table
of values for a while, we find that the promise is
satisfied for the string 011.

511
56:25.902 --> 56:32.010
000 and 011 are partners. XORing either one of them
by s gives us the other,

512
56:32.010 --> 56:41.160
and they take the same output value, which is 10011 in this particular case, and no other strings produce
that same output string.

513
56:41.160 --> 56:48.960
001 and 010 are partners because XORing either
one by s gives the other, and they produce the same output value,

514
56:48.960 --> 56:52.440
which again, isn't produced
by any other string.

515
56:52.440 --> 57:01.398
And the situation is
similar for 100 and 111 as well as 101 and 110.

516
57:01.398 --> 57:08.130
So if the input to the
problem is this function, the correct answer is the string 011.

517
57:08.130 --> 57:15.120
Like I said before, most functions don't satisfy this promise, it's a very specific condition.

518
57:15.120 --> 57:20.640
It should also be noted that
if the promise is satisfied, it can only be satisfied for one string s.

519
57:20.640 --> 57:25.380
So there's always only one
correct answer to this problem.

520
57:25.380 --> 57:34.080
So that is Simon's problem. Like I said, it's hard to imagine a practical situation in which you'd wanna solve this problem,

521
57:34.080 --> 57:42.360
but that isn't the point. The point is to try to figure out what quantum computers are good at, and it turns out that they're far superior

522
57:42.360 --> 57:46.680
to classical algorithms for
solving this particular problem.

523
57:46.680 --> 57:52.650
Now let's take a look
at Simon's algorithm, which solves Simon's problem.

524
57:52.650 --> 58:00.600
The algorithm consists of
running the quantum circuit that you see here several times, followed by a classical
post-processing step,

525
58:00.600 --> 58:05.970
and we'll be more specific about what several
times means a bit later.

526
58:05.970 --> 58:13.800
The circuit looks very similar
to the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit, this time because the function
f maps n bits to m bits,

527
58:13.800 --> 58:19.980
the query gate is different. Rather than just a single
qubit on the bottom, we now have m qubits on the bottom

528
58:19.980 --> 58:23.850
and n on the top like before.

529
58:23.850 --> 58:30.900
A key difference is that we're
not setting up a minus state or multiple minus states on the bottom.

530
58:30.900 --> 58:37.980
These bottom qubits are all
initialized to the 0 state, and those states go straight
into the query gate.

